# Java Exception Handling

## Use Specific Exceptions
- Throw the most specific exception type: `IllegalArgumentException`, `NoSuchElementException`, not generic `RuntimeException`
- Create custom domain exceptions for business errors (`InsufficientFundsException`, `OrderNotFoundException`)
- Custom exceptions should extend `RuntimeException` unless the caller is expected to handle recovery

## Resource Management
- Always use try-with-resources for `AutoCloseable` resources
- Attach secondary cleanup failures via `Throwable.addSuppressed()`
- Never rely on `finalize()` -- it is deprecated and unreliable

## Fail-Fast Validation
- Validate inputs at method entry: `Objects.requireNonNull(param, "param must not be null")`
- Throw `IllegalArgumentException` for invalid values, `IllegalStateException` for invalid object state
- Do not allow invalid state to propagate through the system

## Exception Chaining
- Always pass the original exception as the cause: `throw new DomainException("msg", cause)`
- Preserve full stack traces for debugging
- Translate exceptions at API boundaries using centralized handlers

## Logging Discipline
- Log at the boundary that decides the response, not at every catch site
- Never log-and-throw the same exception -- pick one
- Use structured logging with correlation IDs and error codes
- Log stack traces at ERROR level only for unexpected failures

## Do Not Catch
- Never catch `Throwable` or `Error` -- let JVM errors propagate
- Never catch bare `Exception` in business logic -- catch specific types
- Never silently swallow exceptions with empty catch blocks

## Interruption
- `InterruptedException`: propagate or restore with `Thread.currentThread().interrupt()`
- Never ignore `InterruptedException`

## Async/Reactive Propagation
- In `CompletableFuture`: use `exceptionally()` or `handle()` for error paths
- Propagate failures without blocking; honor cancellation semantics

## Retry Policy
- Retry only idempotent operations
- Use bounded attempts with exponential backoff and jitter
- Enforce timeouts on all remote calls

## API Boundary Translation
- Map internal exceptions to HTTP status codes / Problem Details at controller level
- Use `@ControllerAdvice` / `@ExceptionHandler` in Spring for centralized mapping
- Never expose internal stack traces or class names in API responses

